  readTime="5 min read"
>

  <p>Most sellers assume their house will sell. You list it, you wait, you get offers. That's how it's supposed to work. But a lot of houses don't follow that script — and when you're sitting at 60, 90, or 120 days on the market without a clean offer, the stress compounds fast. Carrying costs keep running. Your plans are on hold. And you're not sure if the right move is to drop the price, take it off the market, or try something else entirely.</p>

  <p>I've bought a lot of houses from sellers in exactly that situation. Here's how I'd think through it.</p>

  <h2>First, Figure Out Why It Didn't Sell</h2>

  <p>There are basically three reasons a house sits on the market without selling, and the answer changes what you should do next.</p>

  <p><strong>The price is wrong.</strong> This is the most common one and the hardest one to hear. If the house is priced above what comparable homes in the neighborhood are actually selling for, buyers will see it, maybe tour it, and move on. They know the market. Dropping the price — sometimes significantly — is the fastest way to unstick a listing. The question is whether you can afford to drop it far enough to compete.</p>

  <p><strong>The house has issues that kill financing.</strong> FHA and VA loans have minimum property standards. A roof that's at the end of its life, foundation movement, electrical that hasn't been updated since the 1970s — these can kill a financed sale even if a buyer wants the house. When the buyer pool is mostly people using loans, a house with real condition issues can sit indefinitely. Your market is effectively limited to cash buyers who can work around the condition.</p>

  <p><strong>The location is working against you.</strong> Some neighborhoods in Wichita move fast. Others are slower — higher crime, lower income area, near an industrial corridor. If the house is in an area where demand is genuinely lower, you can't out-market your way to a fast sale. You adjust price to match demand or you find a buyer who specializes in that area.</p>

  <p>Usually when a house won't sell it's some combination of all three. Figuring out which one is driving it determines your next move.</p>

  <h2>Option 1: Cut the Price and Relist</h2>

  <p>If the price is the primary issue and you have room to drop it, relisting at a significantly lower number can work. I mean significantly — a $5,000 price reduction on a house that's $25,000 overpriced doesn't move the needle. You want to price it below comparable homes, not at them, to create urgency.</p>

  <p>The problem is this takes time. A new listing gets attention for the first few weeks, then interest drops off. If you need the house sold in the next 30–60 days, relisting is a gamble.</p>

  <h2>Option 2: Rent It Out</h2>

  <p>If you don't absolutely need the proceeds right now, turning the house into a rental buys you time. You cover your carrying costs, the market has time to move, and you can try to sell again later.</p>

  <p>This only works if you're not in a situation that requires selling — divorce, estate, financial pressure, relocation. And becoming a landlord has its own complications. If the house is in rough shape, finding and keeping tenants isn't always easy either.</p>

  <h2>Option 3: Sell Directly to a Cash Buyer</h2>

  <p>This is the option most sellers don't seriously consider until they've exhausted the others. I'd argue it's worth running the numbers on earlier.</p>

  <p>Here's what a direct sale actually looks like versus a traditional listing that finally closes:</p>

  <p>On a traditional sale, you're typically paying 5–6% in agent commissions, 1–2% in closing costs, and whatever the buyer asks for in repair credits after inspection. On a $175,000 sale, that's $12,000–$15,000 off the top before you've touched anything. Add in 3–4 months of carrying costs — mortgage, taxes, insurance, utilities — and you're looking at another $3,000–$6,000 depending on your situation. By the time you close, the net proceeds on a $175,000 listing might be $155,000–$160,000.</p>

  <p>A cash offer comes in lower than the listing price, but it's net — no commissions, no repair credits, no carrying costs for another four months. The gap is often smaller than sellers expect. Sometimes it's not there at all.</p>

  <p>The other thing a cash sale gives you is certainty. Financed deals fall through — sometimes at the last minute, after you've made plans based on that closing date. Cash closes don't have financing contingencies. When we say we'll close, we close.</p>

  <h2>What I'd Actually Do If It Were My House</h2>

  <p>If the house had been on the market 90+ days with no real offers, I'd stop and do two things before making a decision.</p>

  <p>First, I'd get an honest conversation with a cash buyer — not a Zestimate, not a "we buy houses" mailer with a fake number on it, but an actual sit-down where someone walks through the math with you. What would an offer be, what are the carrying costs you'd save, what does the net look like. That's a 20-minute phone call and it's free.</p>

  <p>Second, I'd look hard at why it didn't sell. If it's strictly price and I have room to drop it, I might try one more aggressive relist. If it's condition or location, relisting at any price is probably just more time and carrying costs.</p>

  <p>Either way, knowing your actual options makes the decision a lot easier.</p>

  <h2>The Wichita Market Right Now</h2>

  <p>Wichita is a mid-sized market with real variation by neighborhood. Move-in-ready houses in areas like Andover, Derby, and the east side of Wichita proper tend to sell relatively quickly when priced right. Houses that need work, or that are in slower-moving neighborhoods, sit longer and compete with a smaller buyer pool.</p>

  <p>If your house has been on the market without selling, the problem is almost never that no buyer exists — it's that the right buyer for your specific house hasn't found it yet, or the price doesn't work for who's looking. A cash buyer is often the right buyer for houses that the traditional market isn't absorbing.</p>

